<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="multi-project-hosting">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>Strategies for hosting 2-5 web projects on one VPS: port allocation by 100-range convention, nginx reverse proxy, Cloudflare origin certs, shared database decisions, and resource planning.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>hosting</tag>
      <tag>nginx</tag>
      <tag>multi-project</tag>
      <tag>port-allocation</tag>
      <tag>vps</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Multi-Project Hosting</title>
    <summary>Strategies for hosting 2-5 web projects on a single VPS: port allocation by 100-range convention with a /srv/port-registry.txt as single source of truth, nginx multi-domain reverse proxy with shared snippets, Cloudflare DNS and origin certificates, shared vs isolated PostgreSQL/Redis decision matrix, and resource budget planning.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Adding a second project to a server without a port convention creates conflicts. Without a registry, agents and humans lose track of what is bound where. nginx server blocks provide cheap domain isolation without separate servers. Shared PostgreSQL/Redis is the right trade-off for solo devs at 2-5 projects: lower resource use, simpler backups, acceptable blast radius.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Adding a second project to an existing VPS (port allocation and nginx config needed)</item>
        <item>Configuring nginx for a new domain with SSL via Cloudflare origin cert</item>
        <item>Deciding whether to share PostgreSQL/Redis or isolate per project</item>
        <item>Auditing resource utilization to determine whether to split to a second server</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-project servers where isolation is not a concern</item>
        <item>Kubernetes/Swarm clusters — use cluster-native ingress instead</item>
        <item>Serverless or PaaS deployments (Vercel, Railway) — hosting is abstracted</item>
        <item>Projects with strict compliance requirements mandating physical isolation</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="port-allocation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Allocate 100-port blocks per project (8100-8199, 8200-8299) and maintain /srv/port-registry.txt as the single source of truth for all active port assignments.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a registry, port conflicts are discovered at service startup, often during a deploy. The registry makes the full picture visible in one place so a new project can pick a free range without scanning running processes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always bind application ports to 127.0.0.1, never 0.0.0.0; nginx is the only service that listens on public interfaces.</statement>
        <rationale>Binding to 0.0.0.0 exposes application ports directly to the internet. A misconfigured firewall or missed ufw rule becomes a direct breach. Binding to 127.0.0.1 makes nginx the mandatory ingress point.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="port-range-convention">
        <list>
          <item>5432 — PostgreSQL (Docker, shared, 127.0.0.1 only)</item>
          <item>5672 — RabbitMQ AMQP (Docker, shared, 127.0.0.1 only)</item>
          <item>6379 — Redis (Docker, shared, 127.0.0.1 only)</item>
          <item>8100-8199 — Project 1 (API at +00, SPA at +01, admin at +10, dev at +50)</item>
          <item>8200-8299 — Project 2</item>
          <item>8300-8399 — Project 3</item>
          <item>8400-8499, 8500-8599 — Reserved for future projects</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# /srv/port-registry.txt
# Format: PORT    SERVICE              PROJECT      BIND        NOTES
5432    postgresql           shared      127.0.0.1   Docker container
5672    rabbitmq-amqp        shared      127.0.0.1   Message broker
6379    redis                shared      127.0.0.1   Cache + Celery backend
15672   rabbitmq-mgmt        shared      127.0.0.1   RabbitMQ admin UI

8100    nero-api             nero        127.0.0.1   FastAPI API + WebSocket
8101    nero-web             nero        127.0.0.1   React SPA

8200    meetingtax-be        meetingtax  127.0.0.1   FastAPI API
8201    meetingtax-fe        meetingtax  127.0.0.1   Next.js frontend
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <section name="directory-layout">
        <list>
          <item>/srv/project-name/ — runtime root (code, venvs, .env)</item>
          <item>/srv/project-name/.env — project secrets (chmod 600)</item>
          <item>/srv/port-registry.txt — server-wide port registry</item>
          <item>~/.config/systemd/user/project-name-*.service — systemd service files</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="nginx-multi-domain">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use shared snippets (/etc/nginx/snippets/) for proxy-params, security headers, and SSL params; never copy-paste these blocks into each site config.</statement>
        <rationale>Copied blocks diverge over time. When a security header needs updating across 5 sites, a single snippets/security-headers.conf edit covers all of them in one nginx reload.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always run nginx -t before reload; a config syntax error stops the reload and leaves nginx serving stale config without error feedback.</statement>
        <rationale>nginx reload only takes effect if the new config parses successfully. Without testing first, a typo in a new site block causes a silent failure where the intended site config never loads.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="server-block-pattern">
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
# /etc/nginx/sites-available/example.com
# Enable: sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/example.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
# Test:   sudo nginx -t
# Reload: sudo systemctl reload nginx

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/ssl/example.com/cert.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/ssl/example.com/key.pem;

    include snippets/security-headers.conf;

    access_log /var/log/nginx/example.com.access.log;
    error_log  /var/log/nginx/example.com.error.log;

    location /api/ {
        include snippets/proxy-params.conf;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8200;
    }

    location /ws {
        include snippets/proxy-params.conf;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8200;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
        proxy_read_timeout 86400;
    }

    location / {
        include snippets/proxy-params.conf;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8201;
    }
}
          ]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>
      <section name="shared-snippets">
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
# /etc/nginx/snippets/proxy-params.conf
proxy_set_header Host $host;
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
proxy_http_version 1.1;
proxy_connect_timeout 60s;
proxy_send_timeout 60s;
proxy_read_timeout 60s;
proxy_buffering off;

# /etc/nginx/snippets/security-headers.conf
add_header X-Frame-Options "SAMEORIGIN" always;
add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;
add_header X-XSS-Protection "1; mode=block" always;
add_header Referrer-Policy "strict-origin-when-cross-origin" always;
add_header Permissions-Policy "camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()" always;
          ]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>
      <section name="cloudflare-ssl">
        <rule>
          <statement>Use Cloudflare Origin Certificates with Full (Strict) SSL mode; origin certs are free, have 15-year validity, and require no renewal automation.</statement>
          <rationale>Let's Encrypt certs require renewal every 90 days and a certbot cron job. With Cloudflare acting as the termination point, origin certs only need to be trusted by Cloudflare — no public CA required.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Install a Cloudflare origin certificate for a domain
sudo mkdir -p /etc/ssl/example.com
# Paste cert from Cloudflare dashboard → SSL/TLS → Origin Server → Create Certificate
sudo nano /etc/ssl/example.com/cert.pem
sudo nano /etc/ssl/example.com/key.pem
sudo chmod 600 /etc/ssl/example.com/key.pem
sudo chmod 644 /etc/ssl/example.com/cert.pem
          ]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>
      <section name="enable-workflow">
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Standard workflow to enable a new site
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/example.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t && sudo systemctl reload nginx

# Verify site is active
curl -I https://example.com
          ]]></code>
        </example>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Editing site configs directly in sites-enabled/ instead of sites-available/.</description>
          <reason>sites-enabled/ should contain only symlinks. Editing files directly in sites-enabled/ breaks the sites-available/ as the authoritative config location and complicates backup and version control.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="shared-services">
      <rule>
        <statement>For solo developers running 2-5 projects on one VPS, use a single shared PostgreSQL instance with separate databases per project, and a single Redis with separate DB numbers or key prefixes.</statement>
        <rationale>A solo VPS with 30GB RAM can run one well-tuned PostgreSQL instance versus four independent instances, each consuming 500MB+ for shared_buffers alone. Shared services cost less RAM and have a single backup target. The blast radius of a single shared instance failure is acceptable when one developer can fix it immediately.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="decision-matrix">
        <list>
          <item>Shared: lower RAM and disk consumption, single backup, simpler monitoring</item>
          <item>Shared: appropriate for solo dev at 2-5 projects with acceptable isolation</item>
          <item>Isolated: required for compliance, customer data segregation, or team environments</item>
          <item>Isolated: appropriate when one project needs a different PostgreSQL major version</item>
          <item>Isolated: appropriate when a single project justifies dedicated hosting costs</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="postgresql-per-project">
        <rule>
          <statement>Create a separate database and a dedicated database user per project; never share credentials between projects.</statement>
          <rationale>Separate users mean a compromised project cannot query another project's database. Separate databases make per-project backups and restores possible without touching other projects.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="sql"><![CDATA[
-- In shared PostgreSQL (docker exec -it nero-postgres psql -U postgres)

-- Create per-project databases
CREATE DATABASE nero;
CREATE DATABASE meetingtax;
CREATE DATABASE eulaguard;

-- Create per-project users (isolated credentials)
CREATE USER nero_user WITH PASSWORD 'generate-with-openssl';
CREATE USER mtax_user WITH PASSWORD 'generate-with-openssl';
CREATE USER eulag_user WITH PASSWORD 'generate-with-openssl';

-- Grant access — each user can only access its own database
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE nero TO nero_user;
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE meetingtax TO mtax_user;
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE eulaguard TO eulag_user;

-- Set ownership so schema creation works
ALTER DATABASE nero OWNER TO nero_user;
ALTER DATABASE meetingtax OWNER TO mtax_user;
ALTER DATABASE eulaguard OWNER TO eulag_user;
          ]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>
      <section name="redis-isolation">
        <list>
          <item>DB number allocation: DB 0 = project 1, DB 1 = project 1 Celery, DB 2 = project 2, DB 3 = project 3</item>
          <item>Key prefix alternative: nero:cache:*, nero:sessions:*, mtax:cache:* (all in DB 0)</item>
          <item>DB numbers are simpler to reason about; key prefixes are more flexible but require discipline</item>
          <item>Redis ships with 16 databases (0-15) by default — sufficient for up to 8 projects with 2 DBs each</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="resource-planning">
        <list>
          <item>PostgreSQL shared_buffers: set to 25% of RAM allocated to postgres (e.g., 2GB for an 8GB budget)</item>
          <item>Redis maxmemory: set to prevent Redis from consuming all available RAM on cache growth</item>
          <item>Per-service MemoryMax in systemd units: hard limit that triggers OOM kill before system OOM</item>
          <item>Signal to split to a second server: consistent memory pressure above 85% for 7+ days</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/nginx-site.conf" purpose="Generic nginx server block template with HTTP redirect, SSL, proxy, WebSocket"/>
      <template path="templates/port-registry.txt" purpose="Port allocation registry with format and example entries"/>
      <template path="templates/setup-project.sh" purpose="Create runtime dirs, .env, systemd service, update port registry for a new project"/>
      <template path="templates/add-database.sh" purpose="Create PostgreSQL database and user in shared Docker instance"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
